commentBody:
@Barry Ancona

My prediction is that there will be a very high number--over 500--of comments for this one.

This is a trick that has been done 18 times previously, all but one of which was in this century, but there's always a big contingent that's never seen it before.

@Steve L

Suddenly I have an idea about how I could increase my "recommends":  a simple name change.

But I'd have to learn to write shorter comments.  Ah, forget it.

@Maverator

Here's a version that stays put:

<a href="https://www.xwordinfo.com/Crossword?date=5/8/2025" target="_blank">https://www.xwordinfo.com/Crossword?date=5/8/2025</a>

@Steve L

Possibly but not in my case. I started working the crossword when I was about 10, which is a lot of decades ago. What the defenders don't seem to understand is that our beef is more with the execution than with the gimmick. I love rebuses and other tricks, I love me some difficulty, but this one was just a dud. Too much really strange cluing, too much obscure trivia, for a trick that wasn't that dazzling. To me it was more trouble than it was worth. 

This is expressly stated as being my opinion, not facts in need of refuting. I will go check out the one you refer to. I've missed a few days and am curious.

@Beth C

I too got (T)AILS and BUTTS OUT and expected the other words missing letters to be butt synonyms. 

Congratulations on your success with late-week puzzles! You have a great attitude about them. I don’t think it will be long before you’re able to solve most of them easily.

@Steve L

Made me lol.

It was a single elimination.

@Dan
I had this problem as well.  Too much to keep track of in my head.  Someone suggested acting like it's a rebus and adding the missing letter into the corresponding square on the edge, which allows you to keep track of things.  

The downside is you have to go back at the end and take out the rebuses in order to get the happy music.

@Mimi

"over 25 entries being either foreign language, proper (capitalized) words, archaic, slang, and acronyms/initialisms"

lol. God forbid the puzzle include things that are slightly less difficult than extremely recent pop culture, clues that essentially give you the answer, or anything else that might challenge you at all, like the puzzle used to include before its sole goal became money over quality

@dutchiris

"Butt jokes can trigger hysterical laughter from children"

🙋‍♀️And inner children!

@Barry Ancona

Are we talking about the same thing? I’m referring to the fact that mayo to mayo in Spanish is one AÑO, but the default of the grid’s tilde-less ANO means something very today’s theme-adjacent, though not necessarily passing the breakfast test. 

What are you referring to and why are we now discussing anything in Portuguese?

@T

I'm glad you enjoyed the puzzle - it balances out my annoyance with it :D

It so cool how different people can be, how differently they think and what they consider gimmes. Your gimmes were arcane mysteries to me, and my puny mind just could not wrap itself around the theme :p

@marty

If you've been doing the puzzle for over 30 years, you should know that Thursday puzzles are almost always "weird" in some way or another.  You should allow yourself to take the day off if you don't like them.

As for me, the weirder, the better!  I look forward to Thursday, and I'm disappointed if the puzzle isn't weird.

@Mr Dave

And that’s just a single example from the last year!

Now consider that the average late-week puzzle difficulty was something like 2x-3x harder up until ~5 years ago, and there have been plenty of creative/diabolical Thursdays, and some *very* hard Fridays and Saturdays, along the way…

@alan

Float like a butterfly, sting like a bee.

Pretty dang silver-tongued for a boxer.

@Petrol

I always look for Mike's comments, too.

Mic drop.

@Mark
Continue your New Life by printing out the puzzles and using a FriXion pen to solve.  SO fun!
Congrats....although we did move to a CCRC here in MS (kinda near one of the offspring and lotsa doctors, ha ha.)  However, we do not feel we are surrounded by 'decrepit' folks, just peers who have life stories, hobbies, interests, and determination.

@Mean Old Lady

Usually I solve the puzzle while lying in bed. So although I fully understand why I should, I probably won’t ever print out a puzzle. 

It’s one thing to be surrounded by interesting people. There are some in Santa Fe, but many more have more money than brains. Like many popular places in the world, Santa Fe has been ruined by its popularity and overrun with entitled, boring rich people. I am much happier among a much more diverse population.

@Barry Ancona
Maybe it's just burnout. I had a 30-day streak, and I was really willing to dig deep because I didn't want to lose it. Now that it's over, I don't seem to have the gumption for a puzzle like this.

I guess you're right about Sundays. Somehow I never noticed.

@retired, with cat

We Cat People must stick together!
I do print out my puzzles and solve with pen, and this was great fun as well as very challenging...  I finished with an error (Natick crossing) but Jimmy-crack-corn and I don't care!  I had fun anyway!

@Jess

The worst kind of whining, IMO: whining about people voicing their opinions. News flash: it is perfectly fine for people to not like things, and to be emotional about it.

I much prefer a good rant to sickly sweet praise.

@Andrzej

Because if enough people shout that something should not exist, eventually, it may not exist, and that will be sad for the folks who enjoy that thing (assuming "that thing" is not infringing on anyone else's rights.) 

By the way, your comments never come across that way.

@Michael
And yet, I did it without printing, as did many others here.

Just because you didn't like a puzzle doesn't mean it's bad.

@Sam Lyons

Thank you from a solver who appreciates your sparkle and bloom!

Perhaps "no solver left behind" means sometimes the tired rider whines? ☺️

@Sam Lyons

Frustrated anger is a great toehold if your goal is to divide a society. It's easy to feed via social media, movies, any number of ways.

In the short term it feels more satisfying to throw something across the room rather than to calm down, think about the problem, and find a solution. If you encourage the first approach you can sow a lot of chaos.

@TholosTB

“I couldn’t see the pattern online of which ones were overflowing and which ones weren’t”

What do you mean? Are you saying that the print edition included a visual cue that identified the theme entries?

@Dan

No.

LIVETH the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "to live"

@Trish

"He TOOK A DIG AT the emus by pointing out they couldn't fly. Now all his posts vanish without a trace."

Figure of speech.

@kilaueabart

Seriously, just for figuring out the trick and being resourceful about it, you're deserving of what you always refer to as an "artificial" streak. 
Tip of the hat, sir.

@Eric Ressner

But if you enter the “out-letters” in rebuses, then they aren’t *out* of the grid, right?

Also, the crosses don’t work if you use rebuses for the theme answers.

@Ors

That’s exactly my issue.  I realized that the shortened answers were in symmetrical locations, which ultimately help to know where to apply the theme, but that was not a very satisfying solution .

Add to that the fact that the missing letters were simply absent for electronic solvers and I doubt very many picked up on the significance of “butt out” as any kind of clue.

@Nitpicker

BUTT OUT is what is known as a revealer. You can recognize it by its two-part composition; the second half, "and a hint to the four sides of the puzzle," is what gives you the necessary information.

I'd bet most solvers picked up of the significance of the hint.
